<div type="definition">

    <p resp="#CH" modified="2020-10-16T16:52:43.149+09:00">AGREE-TO RECEIVE AND THEN HAVE. </p>
    </div>
<div type="notes">
<div type="old-chinese-criteria">
<p>[ASCENDING/DESCENDING[</p>
<p>[ELEVATED/INFORMAL]</p>
<p>[GENERAL/SPECIFIC]</p>
<p>[IMPOLITE/POLITE]</p>
<p>1. The general word for accepting something offered to one is shòu 受, but the distinction with the passive "receive" is not made explicit.</p>
<p>[GENERAL]</p>
<p>2. Fe4ng 奉 is literally to accept something with both arms, enthusiastically, formally.</p>
<p>3. Sho1u 收 refers to accepting and keeping something.</p>
<p>4. Na4 納 refers neutrally to not refusing what one is offered.</p>
<p>5. Bài 拜 is sometimes used by itself to signify very polite acceptance of an offer.</p>
<p>[ASCENDING], [POLITE], [ELEVATED], [SPECIFIC]</p>
